# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: performance-observer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Latency is physically a consequence of the limited velocity at which any physical interaction can propagate.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] The magnitude of this velocity is always less than or equal to the speed of light.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Therefore, every physical system with any physical separation (distance) between cause and effect will experience some sort of latency, regardless of the nature of the stimulation to which it has been exposed.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] The precise definition of latency depends on the system being observed or the nature of the simulation.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] In communications, the lower limit of latency is determined by the medium being used to transfer information.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] In reliable two-way communication systems, latency limits the maximum rate at which information can be transmitted, as there is often a limit on the amount of information that is in-flight at any given moment.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Perceptible latency has a strong effect on user satisfaction and usability in the field of human–machine interaction.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Online games are sensitive to latency (lag), since fast response times to new events occurring during a game session are rewarded while slow response times may carry penalties.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Due to a delay in transmission of game events, a player with a high-latency internet connection may show slow responses in spite of appropriate reaction time.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] This gives players with low-latency connections a technical advantage.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Trading using computers has developed to the point where millisecond improvements in network speeds offer a competitive advantage for financial institutions.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] However, in a non-trivial network, a typical packet will be forwarded over multiple links and gateways, each of which will not begin to forward the packet until it has been completely received.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] In such a network, the minimal latency is the sum of the transmission delay of each link, plus the forwarding latency of each gateway.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] In practice, minimal latency also includes queuing and processing delays.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Queuing delay occurs when a gateway receives multiple packets from different sources heading toward the same destination.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Since typically only one packet can be transmitted at a time, some of the packets must queue for transmission, incurring additional delay.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Processing delays are incurred while a gateway determines what to do with a newly received packet.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Bufferbloat can also cause increased latency that is an order of magnitude or more.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] The combination of propagation, serialization, queuing, and processing delays often produces a complex and variable network latency profile.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Latency limits total throughput in reliable two-way communication systems as described by the bandwidth-delay product.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Latency in optical fiber is largely a function of the speed of light.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] This would equate to a latency of 3.33 μs for every kilometer of path length.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] The index of refraction of most fiber optic cables is about 1.5, meaning that light travels about 1.5 times as fast in a vacuum as it does in the cable.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] This works out to about 5.0 μs of latency for every kilometer.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] In shorter metro networks, higher latency can be experienced due to extra distance in building risers and cross-connects.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] To calculate the latency of a connection, one has to know the distance traveled by the fiber, which is rarely a straight line, since it has to traverse geographic contours and obstacles, such as roads and railway tracks, as well as other rights-of-way.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Due to imperfections in the fiber, light degrades as it is transmitted through it.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] For distances of greater than 100 kilometers, amplifiers or regenerators are deployed.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Latency introduced by these components needs to be taken into account.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Low Earth orbit is sometimes used to cut this delay, at the expense of more complicated satellite tracking on the ground and requiring more satellites in the satellite constellation to ensure continuous coverage.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Audio latency is the delay between when an audio signal enters and when it emerges from a system.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Potential contributors to latency in an audio system include analog-to-digital conversion, buffering, digital signal processing, transmission time, digital-to-analog conversion and the speed of sound in air.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Video latency refers to the degree of delay between the time a transfer of a video stream is requested and the actual time that transfer begins.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Networks that exhibit relatively small delays are known as low-latency networks, while their counterparts are known as high-latency networks.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Any individual workflow within a system of workflows can be subject to some type of operational latency.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] It may even be the case that an individual system may have more than one type of latency, depending on the type of participant or goal-seeking behavior.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] This is best illustrated by the following two examples involving air travel.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] From the point of view of a passenger, latency can be described as follows.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Suppose John Doe flies from London to New York.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] The latency of his trip is the time it takes him to go from his house in England to the hotel he is staying at in New York.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] This is independent of the throughput of the London-New York air link, whether there were 100 passengers a day making the trip or 10000, the latency of the trip would remain the same.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] From the point of view of flight operations personnel, latency can be entirely different.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Consider the staff at the London and New York airports.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Only a limited number of planes are able to make the transatlantic journey, so when one lands, they must prepare it for the return trip as quickly as possible.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] However, cleaning, refueling and loading the cargo can be done at the same time.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Passengers can only be loaded after cleaning is complete.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] The people involved in the turnaround are interested only in the time it takes for their individual tasks.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] When all of the tasks are done at the same time, however, it is possible to reduce the latency to the length of the longest task.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] If some steps have prerequisites, it becomes more difficult to perform all steps in parallel.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] In the example above, the requirement to clean the plane before loading passengers results in a minimum latency longer than any single task.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Any mechanical process encounters limitations modeled by Newtonian physics.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] The behavior of disk drives provides an example of mechanical latency.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Here, it is the time seek time for the actuator arm to be positioned above the appropriate track and then rotational latency for the data encoded on a platter to rotate from its current position to a position under the disk read-and-write head.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Computers run instructions in the context of a process.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] In the context of computer multitasking, the execution of the process can be postponed if other processes are also executing.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] In addition, the operating system can schedule when to perform the action that the process is commanding.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] For example, suppose a process commands that a computer card's voltage output be set high-low-high-low and so on at a rate of 1000 Hz.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] The operating system schedules the process for each transition (high-low or low-high) based on a hardware clock, such as the High Precision Event Timer.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] The latency is the delay between the events generated by the hardware clock and the actual transitions of voltage from high to low or low to high.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Many desktop operating systems have performance limitations that create additional latency.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] The problem may be mitigated with real-time extensions and patches such as PREEMPT RT.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] On embedded systems, the real-time execution of instructions is often supported by a real-time operating system.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Note that in software systems, benchmarking against *average* and *median* latency can be misleading because a few outliers can distort them.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Instead, software architects and software developers should use "99th percentile".
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] In simulation applications, latency refers to the time delay, often measured in milliseconds, between initial input and output clearly discernible to the simulator trainee or simulator subject.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Latency is sometimes also called *transport delay*.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] Some authorities distinguish between latency and transport delay by using the term *latency* in the sense of the extra time delay of a system over and above the reaction time of the vehicle being simulated, but this requires detailed knowledge of the vehicle dynamics and can be controversial.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] In simulators with both visual and motion systems, it is particularly important that the latency of the motion system not be greater than of the visual system, or symptoms of simulator sickness may result.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] This is because, in the real world, motion cues are those of acceleration and are quickly transmitted to the brain, typically in less than 50 milliseconds; this is followed some milliseconds later by a perception of change in the visual scene.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] The visual scene change is essentially one of change of perspective or displacement of objects, such as the horizon, which takes some time to build up to discernible amounts after the initial acceleration that caused the displacement.
[src:performance-observer/latency-engineering] A simulator should, therefore, reflect the real-world situation by ensuring that the motion latency is equal to or less than that of the visual system and not the other way round.
[src:performance-observer/performanceentry] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:performance-observer/performanceentry] It’s been available across browsers since September 2017.
[src:performance-observer/performanceentry] The **`PerformanceEntry`** object encapsulates a single performance metric that is part of the browser's performance timeline.
[src:performance-observer/performanceentry] The Performance API offers built-in metrics which are specialized subclasses of `PerformanceEntry`.
[src:performance-observer/performanceentry] This includes entries for resource loading, event timing, and more.
[src:performance-observer/performanceentry] A performance entry can also be created by calling the `Performance.mark()` or `Performance.measure()` methods at an explicit point in an application.
[src:performance-observer/performanceentry] This allows you to add your own metrics to the performance timeline.
[src:performance-observer/performanceentry] A string representing the name for a performance entry.
[src:performance-observer/performanceentry] A string representing the type of performance metric.
[src:performance-observer/performanceentry] For example, `"mark"` when `PerformanceMark` is used.
[src:performance-observer/performanceentry] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the starting time for the performance metric.
[src:performance-observer/performanceentry] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` representing the duration of the performance entry.
[src:performance-observer/performanceentry] Returns a JSON representation of the `PerformanceEntry` object.
[src:performance-observer/performanceentry] The following example creates `PerformanceEntry` objects that are of the types `PerformanceMark` and `PerformanceMeasure`.
[src:performance-observer/performanceentry] The `PerformanceMark` and `PerformanceMeasure` subclasses inherit the `duration`, `entryType`, `name`, and `startTime` properties from `PerformanceEntry` and set them to their appropriate values.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] The **`observe()`** method of the **`PerformanceObserver`** interface is used to specify the set of performance entry types to observe.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] See `PerformanceEntry.entryType` for a list of entry types and `PerformanceObserver.supportedEntryTypes` for a list of entry types the user agent supports.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] When a matching performance entry is recorded, the performance observer's callback function—set when creating the `PerformanceObserver`—is invoked.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] A boolean flag to indicate whether buffered entries should be queued into the observer's buffer.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] Must be used only with the `type` option.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] A `DOMHighResTimeStamp` defining the threshold for `PerformanceEventTiming` entries.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] Defaults to 104ms and is rounded to the nearest of 8ms.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] May not be used together with the `entryTypes` option.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] An array of strings, each specifying one performance entry type to observe.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] May not be used together with the `type`, `buffered`, or `durationThreshold` options.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] See `PerformanceEntry.entryType` for a list of valid performance entry type names.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] Unrecognized types are ignored, though the browser may output a warning message to the console to help developers debug their code.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] If no valid types are found, `observe()` has no effect.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] A single string specifying exactly one performance entry type to observe.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] This example creates a `PerformanceObserver` and watches for `"mark"` and `"measure"` entry types as specified by the `entryTypes` option given in the `observe()` method.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] The following example retrieves buffered events and subscribes to newer events for resource timing events (`PerformanceResourceTiming`) using the `buffered` and `type` configuration options.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] Whenever you need to configure the observer to use the `buffered` or `durationThreshold` option, use `type` instead of `entryType`.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver-observe] Collecting multiple types of performance entry types will not work otherwise.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver] The **`PerformanceObserver`** interface is used to observe performance measurement events and be notified of new performance entries as they are recorded in the browser's *performance timeline*.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver] Creates and returns a new `PerformanceObserver` object.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver] Returns an array of the `entryType` values supported by the user agent.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver] Specifies the set of entry types to observe.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver] The performance observer's callback function will be invoked when performance entry is recorded for one of the specified `entryTypes`.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver] Stops the performance observer callback from receiving performance entries.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver] Returns the current list of performance entries stored in the performance observer, emptying it out.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver] The following example creates a `PerformanceObserver` watching for "mark" (`PerformanceMark`) and "measure" (`PerformanceMeasure`) events.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserver] The `perfObserver` callback provides a `list` (`PerformanceObserverEntryList`) which allows you to get observed performance entries.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserverentrylist] The **`PerformanceObserverEntryList`** interface is a list of performance events that were explicitly observed via the `observe()` method.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserverentrylist] Returns a list of all explicitly observed `PerformanceEntry` objects.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserverentrylist] Returns a list of all explicitly observed `PerformanceEntry` objects of the given entry type.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserverentrylist] Returns a list of all explicitly observed `PerformanceEntry` objects based on the given name and entry type.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserverentrylist] In the following example, `list` is the `PerformanceObserverEntryList` object.
[src:performance-observer/performanceobserverentrylist] The `getEntries()` method is called to get all explicitly observed `PerformanceEntry` objects which are "measure" and "mark" in this case.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] In software engineering, **profiling** (**program profiling**, **software profiling**) is a form of dynamic program analysis that measures, for example, the space (memory) or time complexity of a program, the usage of particular instructions, or the frequency and duration of function calls.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Most commonly, profiling information serves to aid program optimization, and more specifically, performance engineering.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Profiling is achieved by instrumenting either the program source code or its binary executable form using a tool called a *profiler* (or *code profiler*).
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers may use a number of different techniques, such as event-based, statistical, instrumented, and simulation methods.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers use a wide variety of techniques to collect data, including hardware interrupts, code instrumentation, instruction set simulation, operating system hooks, and performance counters.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Summary profile information is often shown annotated against the source code statements where the events occur, so the size of measurement data is linear to the code size of the program.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] For sequential programs, a summary profile is usually sufficient, but performance problems in parallel programs (waiting for messages or synchronization issues) often depend on the time relationship of events, thus requiring a full trace to get an understanding of what is happening.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] A trace may therefore be initiated at one point in a program and terminated at another point to limit the output.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] This provides the opportunity to switch a trace on or off at any desired point during execution in addition to viewing on-going metrics about the (still executing) program.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] It also provides the opportunity to suspend asynchronous processes at critical points to examine interactions with other parallel processes in more detail.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] A profiler can be applied to an individual method or at the scale of a module or program, to identify performance bottlenecks by making long-running code obvious.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] A profiler can be used to understand code from a timing point of view, with the objective of optimizing it to handle various runtime conditions or various loads.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Profiling results can be ingested by a compiler that provides profile-guided optimization.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Profiling results can be used to guide the design and optimization of an individual algorithm; the Krauss matching wildcards algorithm is an example.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers are built into some application performance management systems that aggregate profiling data to provide insight into transaction workloads in distributed applications.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Performance-analysis tools existed on IBM/360 and IBM/370 platforms from the early 1970s, usually based on timer interrupts which recorded the program status word (PSW) at set timer-intervals to detect "hot spots" in executing code.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] This was an early example of sampling (see below).
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] In early 1974 instruction-set simulators permitted full trace and other performance-monitoring features.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Profiler-driven program analysis on Unix dates back to 1973, when Unix systems included a basic tool, `prof`, which listed each function and how much of program execution time it used.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] In 1982 `gprof` extended the concept to a complete call graph analysis.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] In 1994, Amitabh Srivastava and Alan Eustace of Digital Equipment Corporation published a paper describing ATOM (Analysis Tools with OM).
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] The ATOM platform converts a program into its own profiler: at compile time, it inserts code into the program to be analyzed.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] That inserted code outputs analysis data.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] This technique - modifying a program to analyze itself - is known as "instrumentation".
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] In 2004 both the `gprof` and ATOM papers appeared on the list of the 50 most influential PLDI papers for the 20-year period ending in 1999.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Flat profilers compute the average call times, from the calls, and do not break down the call times based on the callee or the context.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Call graph profilers show the call times, and frequencies of the functions, and also the call-chains involved based on the callee.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] In some tools full context is not preserved.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Input-sensitive profilers add a further dimension to flat or call-graph profilers by relating performance measures to features of the input workloads, such as input size or input values.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] They generate charts that characterize how an application's performance scales as a function of its input.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers, which are also programs themselves, analyze target programs by collecting information on the target program's execution.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Based on their data granularity, which depends upon how profilers collect information, they are classified as *event-based* or *statistical* profilers.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers interrupt program execution to collect information.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Those interrupts can limit time measurement resolution, which implies that timing results should be taken with a grain of salt.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Basic block profilers report a number of machine clock cycles devoted to executing each line of code, or timing based on adding those together; the timings reported per basic block may not reflect a difference between cache hits and misses.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] A sampling profiler probes the target program's call stack at regular intervals using operating system interrupts.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Sampling profiles are typically less numerically accurate and specific, providing only a statistical approximation, but allow the target program to run at near full speed.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] "The actual amount of error is usually more than one sampling period.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] In practice, sampling profilers can often provide a more accurate picture of the target program's execution than other approaches, as they are not as intrusive to the target program and thus don't have as many side effects (such as on memory caches or instruction decoding pipelines).
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Also since they don't create much overhead, they can detect issues that would otherwise be hidden.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] They are also relatively immune to over-evaluating the cost of small, frequently called routines or 'tight' loops.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] They can show the relative amount of time spent in user mode versus interruptible kernel mode such as system call processing.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Unfortunately, running kernel code to handle the interrupts incurs a minor loss of CPU cycles from the target program, diverts cache usage, and cannot distinguish the various tasks occurring in uninterruptible kernel code (microsecond-range activity) from user code.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Dedicated hardware can do better: ARM Cortex-M3 and some recent MIPS processors' JTAG interfaces have a PCSAMPLE register, which samples the program counter in a truly undetectable manner, allowing non-intrusive collection of a flat profile.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Some commonly used statistical profilers for Java/managed code are SmartBear Software's AQtime and Microsoft's CLR Profiler.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Those profilers also support native code profiling, along with Apple Inc.'s Shark (OSX), OProfile (Linux), Intel VTune and Parallel Amplifier (part of Intel Parallel Studio), and Oracle Performance Analyzer, among others.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] This technique effectively adds instructions to the target program to collect the required information.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Note that instrumenting a program can cause performance changes, and may in some cases lead to inaccurate results and/or heisenbugs.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] The effect will depend on what information is being collected, on the level of timing details reported, and on whether basic block profiling is used in conjunction with instrumentation.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] For example, adding code to count every procedure/routine call will probably have less effect than counting how many times each statement is obeyed.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] A few computers have special hardware to collect information; in this case the impact on the program is minimal.
[src:performance-observer/profiling-computer-programming] Instrumentation is key to determining the level of control and amount of time resolution available to the profilers.
